title: Go on a walk
description: Challenge yourself to leave your cell phone in your purse or pocket. Admire the view. Stop and smell the roses.

title: Organize something
description: Don’t tackle a huge organizational project like your closet. Instead, choose something small and manageable—your underwear drawer, your pantry, or that crowded bookshelf—so you won’t be intimidated. Get rid of things.

title: Watch music videos
description: Here are some of my favorites to get you started: “Downtown” by Macklemore, “Let’s Have a Kiki” by Scissor Sisters, “Hideaway” by Kiesza, and “Ego” by Beyoncé.

title: Call an old friend
description: Call an old friend you haven’t talked to in forever. Catch up or leave a friendly voicemail.

title: Meditate
description: Download a free app and follow along as you learn to be more in tune with your breathing, body, heart, and mind.

title: Make something!
description: Scour your pantry and fridge. Use the ingredients you have on hand to make a scrumptious salad.

title: Plan a party
description: Plan a party because life is too short not to plan parties. Need a reason for the party?

title: Get lost on Pinterest
description: Not sure how to style your new black pencil skirt? Need a theme for your baby’s first birthday party? Thinking about painting your kitchen chairs? Pinterest is full of ideas on all of these topics and so much more.

title: Bake
description: Whip up a batch of chocolate chip cookies, ricotta orange pound cake, or banana bread. Then surprise a loved one with your delicious creation.

title: Do a puzzle
description: Or a crossword! They’re free in virtually every newspaper.

title: Dance
description: Blast your favorite song and get your groove on. If singing is more your thing, turn up your most beloved Disney classic, and belt it at the top of your lungs.

title: Go to the library
description: Cooking, decorating, historical fiction—find a section of books that you enjoy, check out a few, and take them home to read.

title: Learn about wine
description: Whether you’re into sparkling rosé or Argentinean malbec, get to know how it’s made, who the best producers are, and what pairs well with it. Remember, one of the best ways to learn about wine is to drink as much of it as you can.

title: Play a game
description: Pull out an old-school board game, a pack of cards, or your computer.
